elements.documentation:
The model currently does not have a strong idea of "Behavior".

This diagram shows two different concepts that are disjoint in concept space.  The two concepts will be merged when we generate a realized component.

Concepts are slices through state-space in which we define the necessary state variables to describe the concept.  The minimum set of state variables necessary to describe the concept are used.  They are captured as Properties on a Characterization that characterizes the component.  The component Characterization is symmetrically redefined (BST-ed) to create Characterizations for its states that conform to the component Characterization.

The first concept is a Conceptual Camera.  The Conceptual Camera has modes that allow the user to calibrate, take pictures, etc.  There are certain constraints that are true for all time for the Conceptual Camera.  These constraints are captured in a Characterization that characterizes the Conceptual Camera itself.  There are also certain constraints that are true for specific states of the Conceptual Camera.  These constraints are captured in a Characterization that characterizes the individual states of the Conceptual Camera.  Because these states are additional constraints (in addition to the constraints imposed on the Conceptual Camera for all time), the state Characterizations specialize the component Characterization.

The pattern used for the Conceptual PowerLoad Component the same as that used for the Conceptual Camera.  The difference is that I could actually think of constraints for the states of the Conceptual PowerLoad Component, so the On and Off constraints are not just placeholders.

elements.documentation:
Document Purpose:
The Purpose of this document is to describe 1) the Scenario patterns we intend to use, 2) some validations to make sure the patterns are being followed, and 3) some examples of how we can use the patterns to perform analyses.  Most of the analyses are going to be done by external tools, so the last part will largely be restricted to extracting the necessary information from the pattern to perform an analysis.

The current model does not have a strong idea of "Behavior".  In order to talk about Scenarios, we must first define a representation for Behavior.  Scenarios will then use the elements defined for Behavior and add additional constraint in the form of preconditions, postconditions, temporal constraints, etc.

Document Outline:
Europa has previously defined a pattern for going from a "Conceptual Thing" to a "Realized Thing".  We start in this document by extending that pattern to include patterns for Behavior.  Once we have described how Behavior works in  Conceptual and Realizational space, we describe some Conceptual Scenarios.  We then describe the validation scripts to ensure each part of the transformation is valid.  We then describe scripts to extract the information from the model to perform analyses.
